║                                          ║
║       [ RADIANT PERSUASION ] Lvl 1       ║
║                                          ║
║  Effect: Cynthia’s voice gains +50%      ║
║  Authority. Victor Tan’s [ SKEPTICISM ]  ║
║  is reduced by 20%.                      ║
║  Cost: 3 STAMINA / MINUTE                ║
╚══════════════════════════════════════════╝
```

For the next fifteen minutes, Cynthia didn't just present; she performed. She broke down the loyalty system with a surgical precision that left the Apex executives silent. She used Rodel’s data to prove exactly how much money they were currently losing to inefficient database queries.

"Wait," Victor Tan interrupted, pointing at a slide. "You’re claiming a twenty-two percent reduction in server latency? Based on what? The Skyfall migration logs?"

Aldrich’s face went white. The Skyfall logs were supposed to be buried. 

"Actually," Juan said, stepping forward from the back of the room. 

All eyes turned to him. The **[ CORPORATE INVISIBILITY ]** snapped. 

"The data is based on the unedited logs from the Q3 audit," Juan said, his voice steady. "We used the anomalies from the migration to stress-test the new proposed architecture. The twenty-two percent is a conservative estimate."

Aldrich looked like he wanted to murder Juan right there in the boardroom. But Victor Tan was staring at the screen.

"Unedited logs," Victor repeated. "I like unedited logs. They’re much more interesting than Ferrari brochures."

He looked at Cynthia, then at Juan, and finally, with a look of profound disappointment, at Aldrich.

"Pinnacle Systems," Victor said, standing up. "Your 'Data Guy' and your 'Presentation Queen' just saved your contract. I’ll send the intent to sign by end of day. But let's be clear: I want these two on the implementation team. Not you, Mr. Santos. You can go back to your car dealership."

The room was silent. 

